text: Reuters Insider - Trading at Noon:  Rally doesn't make much sense,  says Multivariate's Wolff
Texto: Click the following link to watch video: https://share.insider.thomsonreuters.com/link?entryId=1_7cg2jehv&referenceId=1_7cg2jehv&pageId=ReutersNewsSource: Reuters InsiderDescription: Multivariate Managing Partner Max Wolff explains why he doesn't believe in the market rally and what concerns him. He also discusses areas where he sees opportunity.Short Link: https://refini.tv/2yEj16EVideo Transcript:Hi everybody. Welcome to Trading at Noon. I am Leah Duncan. More optimism about potential coronavirus vaccines is contributing to gains on Wall Street today. US biotech group Novavax is gaining more than 10% as it enrolls humans to begin testing a vaccine candidate. Merck, meanwhile, said it plans to develop two vaccines. Also, the reopening of the US continues. Some traders returned to the floor of the New York Stock Exchange for the first time since March. The exchange opened its doors to about a quarter of the usual number of workers. They were screened upon entry and asked to avoid public transportation. California, meanwhile, decided to reopen in-store retail businesses and places of worship. On the data front, consumer confidence actually edged higher in the month of May and new home sales in April topped forecasts. Right now, the S&P 500 is up roughly 1.7% with all 11 sectors higher. The Dow is rising 2.4%, led by Raytheon Technologies, Goldman Sachs and JPMorgan Chase. The NASDAQ is adding 0.75% with financials having the best day. For more, let's bring in Max Wolff, Managing Partner of Multivariate. Max, a pleasure to have you on the show with me today on this Tuesday. Stocks are rallying, the S&P crossing key 3,000 level, the Dow up 25,000. President Trump touting the gains in the market today. Do you see a further move higher here? Sure, anything's possible. I mean, look, this is clearly now the asylum being run by its inmates and they can do whatever they want to do. And you can get as excited as you can about $4 trillion or $5 trillion worth of buying from the Fed. And the Fed is running around, propping up all the things that should be selling off. And so, this is a rally that doesn't make much sense, that's led by the most vulnerable. And to be confident, you have to believe that the Federal Reserve will eventually have some $100 trillion balance sheet where they have bought everything you ever bought by accident. And an increasing number of highly vulnerable positions that were bought on purpose. If you believe gravity eventually holds, that however beautiful the balloon looks, tossed in the breeze, eventually, the air inside the balloon achieves density that's similar to the air around it and the balloon makes its trip back down to earth. So, no validity here in the fundamentals basis, but this can last a while. Now, the economic data that we've been getting so far has been pretty dismal, Max, in terms of the numbers for the month of April, but we had improvement in consumer confidence today and new home sales. Are you looking at this as signs that the economy has bottomed? No. I'm saying that look, being locked in your house and terrified is much more difficult to survive than being told that it's safe to go back outside, which gives you some euphoria and you have some pent-up demand for sure. The problem is you don't have any income and we haven't even seen what the wounds look like as the water goes out on the legs here. So the head looks okay because it stayed above water and a lot of what a short-term stock market index is, is the attitudes about the future of very wealthy people who may have been substantially disconnected from the realities in the market. But just very clear here, we have not reached the probable bottom. We don't know what lies ahead. We only know that it is a lot worse than the economic situation we had before this began. So, I know we don't want to believe this, and I know the first stage of grieving is denial and we're in it and there's lots of good reason to grieve and there's no good reason for me to be harsh in my judgments, right? That wouldn't help anyone in any way. But this can't last. This is folly.This economic stock market divide, if you will, Max, that we've been seeing, do you think we'll continue to see that for much more time to come. Well, we've seen that largely be the kind of defining story of the last 11 years. So, it has some legs, right? And it's run pretty far. I don't think it would last forever. I mean, the simple way I look at these things, if it's of any value is it basically our earnings are going to come down between 20%, 25% and 40% in the short-term and then at least 10% to 20% in the long term, by which I mean at least a year. That's a very conservative estimate, could be much worse, but that seems reasonable. And we're going to see that well as we generally see a reduction in the multiples when things are tough, right? So, what we're seeing instead is an assumption that earnings come all the way back to and or above where they weren't before. Seems doubtful that it happens really fast. We know that's not going to happen and that somehow sentiment stays up, right? So what we have is an admixture of not admitting how bad it is and getting a lot of stimulus from the Fed. One of the strange ironies here as the Federal Reserve is treating this patient like it's dying, pumping it full of morphine, a defibrillating the heart every five seconds, and the patients saying, I'm fine, I'm fine, I'm fine. Yeah, sure, you could hope for a miracle. But generally when they're hitting you with this much morphine and their zapping your chest every 35 minutes, it's because you're quite, quite a bit far from fine. Let's talk about opportunities in the markets. Max. Are you seeing any areas that you're liking right now, perhaps stemmed even more unloved names?So, I think the consumer defensives are actually kind of cheap here because people have moved on to this sort of overhyped recovery thesis. So, I think some of the sort of boring consumer defensive staples, the soaps, the basic foods, they actually look pretty good. They don't look super expensive because those look like they'll survive for a while. I think given the rising instability in acrimony around the world, the defense names look pretty strong. I think the financials are overvalued here, so I'd be very nervous about those. I think the med space is interesting. I think this sort of healthcare space has some big winners but there's indiscriminate buying in this. I think the hospitals get hit pretty hard. We're starting to see that. And I think people who are relying on various state governments should be selling off, but they're not because the state governments are all telling us that they have plunging receipts and rising demands for various support, which is understandable given the economic circumstance. At very least, we don't have consensus in Washington about bailing out more, right? Maybe a bit from the House, but not from the Senate. So, need both need the president to back this stuff for it to work. So, I feel like steep finances, I would watch very closely to not get kind of pulled into the hype on anything that's too reliant on the states. Last thing is we saw the pace of globalization sort of running in reverse. That's been a key feature since 2016. If the market was paying attention, they would be literally terrified. It would be wise to be terrified of that feature. And that's now proceeding even faster than it was before corona. If you'd look at acrimony between the US and China and major trading blocks around the world, it's everyone for themselves. And that a sort of acceleration of a deglobalizing trend. And just to make it clear to people why I think it's a big deal, 43% of the beleaguered earnings of the S&P 500 last year were for international, right, which means they're exposed to a system in disarray. So real-time production won't work so well going forward because the supply chains are afraid international cooperation is reduced. Earnings are coming down. 41 million Americans have lost their jobs, right? That doesn't go away. You can't wish it away. You can stimulate it into the background and you can hope for the best. And there's nothing wrong with being hopeful, but this is absolutely unsustainable. Interesting stuff there, Max. You raised a lot of very interesting points. What concerns you the most right now?The disconnect, right? So again, I'll use this analogy. This is you visit your uncle, he's had a major heart attack. He's not lying in bed. You get there and he is kicking his head over his heels and doing an incredibly vigorous, high-intensity cross training routine in the room in the hospital. And the part of you says, this is amazing. Uncle Bob is great. Look at this guy. I don't know if I could do that move. And the part of you that's little bit more rational, a little bit more willing to sort of see the situation as it is as opposed to how you hope it is, wow, is this a bad idea? I got to convince this guy to calm down so that the next time I visit him, it's not in a funeral home. That would be the way I would describe this present state of the market. Anything else that you are keeping a close eye on right now? I do think the tech revolution story is real. I think we're going to spend more of our lives online, right? And I think that's interesting, and I think the online names will do well. But I also think that brings to the fore unsettled business about privacy rights. And so, I would be a little bit cautious about being not concerned about privacy. What a lot of people suddenly go online, especially a lot of people doing a lot more online than they're used to, the crime goes online, particularly with high unemployment and inequality, which we now have. So, the worlds criminals will be joining you or are joining you online. And so, I think security is a good area to be invested in. But I also think that issues of privacy and the desire for a little bit more clear rules of the road for online living are coming. And I think some of the big names and tech will be fine, but others were going to have a little bit of a harder time adjusting. The last thing I would say about the markets is when people have no money, they buy less of almost everything. Max Wolff, great to have you on the show. Thank you so much. Thank you. Always a pleasure. Our stocks watch today include United Airlines. It is one of several travel-related firms getting a boost today after reports that Spain and Germany want to ease travel restrictions for the peak summer season. The stock is up more than 10%, but has lost two-thirds of its value this year. And we're also tracking Marvell Tech. Broker Susquehanna raised its price target on the chipmaker's stock. It sees the company benefiting long-term from the move to 5G. However, it sees a weaker environment for network equipment due to coronavirus-driven supply disruptions. Susquehanna raised its price target to $35 from $30 on Marvell. Shares are up 3%. They hit their highest level in more than 14 years earlier in the trading session. Well, that wraps up Trading at Noon on Tuesday. I'm Leah Duncan and this is Reuters. (c) Copyright Thomson Reuters 2020. Click For Restrictions - http://about.reuters.com/fulllegal.asp

text: UPDATE 1-China's Dada Nexus to kick off $500 mln U.S. IPO this week -sources
Texto: Adds details on company's financesBy Joshua Franklin, Scott Murdoch and Julie ZhuNEW YORK/HONG KONG, May 26 (Reuters) - Chinese delivery firm Dada Nexus Ltd DADA.O will launch the investor roadshow for its U.S. initial public offering as early as Wednesday, according to people familiar with the matter, braving U.S.-China tensions over Chinese companies pursuing their stock market debut in New York.The U.S. Senate passed legislation last week that could prevent some Chinese companies from listing on U.S. exchanges unless they follow standards for U.S. audits and regulations. Nasdaq Inc NDAQ.O also tightened listing restrictions for companies from China and other countries.Shanghai-based Dada is backed by Chinese e-commerce firm JD.com JD.O and Walmart Inc WMT.N, the world's largest retailer.Dada aims to sell around $500 million in stock, with JD.com and Bentonville, Arkansas-based Walmart expected to be cornerstone investors, the sources said.Dada and Walmart declined to comment. JD.com did not immediately respond to a request for comment.Investor scrutiny of Chinese IPOs in the United States has increased in the wake of Chinese coffee chain Luckin Coffee's  LK.O announcement in April that some employees had fabricated sales accounts. Chinese firms may also be left with fewer listing options after China said it would seek to tighten its grip on Hong Kong, a popular IPO venue for Chinese companies.  (Full Story)In Dada's favor is an uptick in demand for delivery services during the lockdowns enforced in many cities to curb the COVID-19 outbreak. Dada operates local on-demand delivery platforms JD-Daojia and Dada Now.Shares of Chinese cloud computing company Kingsoft Cloud Holdings Ltd KC.O, expected to benefit from current economic conditions, have risen above their IPO price since going public in New York last month.  (Full Story)Dada's net loss last year widened to 2.46 billion yuan  ($344.97 million) from 2.39 billion yuan in 2018. Net revenue in the first quarter rose to 1.1 billion yuan from 526.5 million yuan a year earlier.($1 = 7.1310 Chinese yuan renminbi) (Reporting by Joshua Franklin in New York, and Scott Murdoch and Julie Zhu in Hong Kong; Editing by Andrea Ricci and Richard Chang)(( joshua.franklin@thomsonreuters.com ; +1 646-223-6356; Reuters Messaging: joshua.franklin.thomsonreuters.com@reuters.net ))(c) Copyright Thomson Reuters 2020.
